<subSubSection id="6894D3871A1BFFA4FF6F8365FDB99A00" pageId="26" pageNumber="177" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="2031800C1A1BFFA4FF6F8365FBEC99EC" blockId="26.[151,1437,942,2013]" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">
<emphasis id="12FA5C1E1A1BFFA4FF6F8365FEEB9955" bold="true" box="[199,322,1122,1148]" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="E78EFB8F1A1BFFA4FEE18364FD939954" authorityName="Bidzilya &amp; Karsholt" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Junnilainen" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[329,570,1123,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Ptycerata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perexigella">
<emphasis id="12FA5C1E1A1BFFA4FEE18364FD939954" box="[329,570,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">Ptycerata perexigella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is well recognisable by its small size (wingspan 8.5– 
<quantity id="E7762DE91A1BFFA4FB3B8365FB4A9954" box="[1171,1251,1122,1149]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="26" pageNumber="177" unit="mm" value="11.0">11 mm</quantity>
), pale forewings uniformly mottled with brown, very indistinct markings and grey hindwings. The male genitalia are unique within 
<taxonomicName id="E78EFB8F1A1BFFA4FF3F83ACFEAD99ED" authorityName="Ely" authorityYear="1910" box="[151,260,1195,1220]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Ptycerata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="12FA5C1E1A1BFFA4FF3F83ACFEAD99ED" box="[151,260,1195,1220]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">Ptycerata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a stout uncus, very broad saccus and phallus bent in the middle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2031800C1A1BFFA4FF6F83C9FB829850" blockId="26.[151,1437,942,2013]" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">
<emphasis id="12FA5C1E1A1BFFA4FF6F83C9FE0599C1" bold="true" box="[199,428,1230,1256]" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">
Adult (
<figureCitation id="B8B59C891A1BFFA4FEB383C9FE3699C1" box="[283,415,1230,1256]" captionStart="FIGURES 22–39" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[216,1427,288,1768]" captionTargetId="figure-64@7.[151,1435,273,1799]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 22–39. Ptycerata spp. Adults. 22–28. P. pudicella 22. Romania, LT (gen. slide 59/10, O. Bidzilya). 23. Slovakia, female. 24. Greece, female (gen. slide 49/20, O. Bidzilya). 25. Turkey, male. 26. Russia, Altai, female (gen. slide 178/19, O. Bidzilya). 27. Russia, Amur region, ST of tripunctella, male. 28. Russia, Primorskiy kray, female. 29–37. P. interstratella. 29. Morocco, Lectotype of A. condensata. 30. Morocco, female (gen. slide 177/20, O. Bidzilya). 31. Russia, Sarepta, LT. 32. Kazakhstan, Charyn river, male.33. Iran, male 34.Kyrgyzstan, male.35–37. Russia,Altai. 35. Male.36. Male. 37. Female. 38, 39. P. perexigella. 38. Uzbekistan, male (gen. slide 6/01, O. Bidzilya). 39. Russia, Altai, male (gen. slide 1100, H. Hendriksen)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5270784" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5270784/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">Figs 38, 39</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Wingspan 8.5– 
<quantity id="E7762DE91A1BFFA4FDF783C9FD0299C0" box="[607,683,1230,1257]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="26" pageNumber="177" unit="mm" value="11.0">11 mm</quantity>
Head, thorax and tegulae white, mixed with scattered light brown; labial palpus weakly upcurved, white, palpomere 2 brown on outer surface, palpomere 3 acute, about 1/2 width and about 1/3 length of palpomere 2; scape white, moderately broadening, flagellomeres white and brown-ringed, covered with short cilia in male. Forewing white densely mixed with light brown, three small indistinct spots in fold and cell, costal margin white without brown irroration. Hindwing and fringe grey.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2031800C1A1BFFA4FF6F8284FD7A98E8" blockId="26.[151,1437,942,2013]" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">Variation. Brown markings partially or completely reduced in some specimens; specimens look darker or lighter depending on the amount of light brown irroration.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2031800C1A1BFFA4FF6F82CCFBE59BC8" blockId="26.[151,1437,942,2013]" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">
<emphasis id="12FA5C1E1A1BFFA4FF6F82CCFDB698CD" bold="true" box="[199,543,1482,1509]" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="B8B59C891A1BFFA4FE2382CDFDBE98CD" box="[395,535,1482,1508]" captionStart="FIGURES 82–85" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[214,1374,931,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-305@20.[200,1387,921,1914]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 82–85. Ptycerata spp. Male genitalia. 82, 83. P. interstratella. 82. Kazakhstan (gen. slide 95/07, O. Bidzilya). 83. Turkey (gen. slide 79/17, O. Bidzilya). 84, 85. P. perexigella. 84. Uzbekistan (gen. slide 6/01, O. Bidzilya). 85. Russia, Altai (gen. slide 1110, H. Hendriksen)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5275455" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5275455/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">Figs 84, 85</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
. Uncus comparatively slender, weakly broadening towards 3/4 length, then narrowing towards rounded posterior margin. Gnathos stout, curved at base, with very broad distal part and short upcurved tip. Tegumen trapezoidal, gradually narrowing posteriorly, lateral flaps curved inwardly and almost joining in middle, anteromedial emargination shallow, extending to 1/3–1/4 length of tegumen. Valva as broad as uncus, extending almost to its apex, direct, parallel-sided, right valva with apex rounded, left valva with distinct pointed apex, both dorsocaudal and ventrocaudal angles not developed. Vinculum slender, band-shaped. Saccus broad, parallel-sided, extended beyond top of pedunculus. Distal part of phallus weakly curved, about half the width and twice as long as moderately inflated caecum, lamina ducti ejaculatorii not examined.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2031800C1A1BFFA4FF6F81ECFBB69A2C" blockId="26.[151,1437,942,2013]" box="[199,1055,1771,1797]" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">Variation. Saccus varies in width and length; see also below under Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2031800C1A1BFFA4FF6F8008FDB99A00" blockId="26.[151,1437,942,2013]" box="[199,528,1806,1833]" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">
<emphasis id="12FA5C1E1A1BFFA4FF6F8008FE3A9A01" bold="true" box="[199,403,1806,1833]" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">Female genitalia.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6894D3871A1BFFA4FF6F8035FCCD9ABF" pageId="26" pageNumber="177" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="2031800C1A1BFFA4FF6F8035FC969A58" blockId="26.[151,1437,942,2013]" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">
<emphasis id="12FA5C1E1A1BFFA4FF6F8035FE8E9A65" bold="true" box="[199,295,1842,1868]" pageId="26" pageNumber="177">Biology.</emphasis>
